<font color="#FF0000">TO DR. SPATZ</font><br>
<tt>Fri Dec 27 22:13:42 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
The crowds that protested the Vietnam War had a right to do so. Thousands of lives were lost to enable them to do so even before Vietnam became the tragedy it had become. I would have given up my life for them to have the freedom to do so as they saw fit.<br><br>
That is, Dr. Spatz, before I returned home to be labeled a murderer, baby killer, and a war monger. This was done to me in 1972 at the San Francisco Airport. I was hurrying to get across the terminal to another flight to Kansas City. The person that did this to me wa only a five year old boy. His &quot;parents&quot; were up against the wall laughing and encouraging the boy to kick me. This boy did so and looked at his parents and laughed. They ran away as I gared at them.<br><br>
So Dr. Spatz, where were you when I had to endure this humiliation? In fact where were all these majority of protestors that never raised a hand against the returning soldiers?
<p><code>-- ahernand@manc.edu  (Alex J Hernandez) </code><p>


